        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>As summarized in  Table 2, we will target  CO J=1-0 of a
star-forming  clump  in  Sextans  A  as  indicated  by  Fig.   1.   We
specifically choose this region as it is bright in far-IR and also has
a large  spatial extension.   As shown  in Fig. 1,  the region  has an
across of 1 arcmin but does  not fill the whole 1 arcmin aperture.  We
thus use two pointings. Some regions in the outer parts of the primary
beam would have reduced sensivity by about 50%, which does not affect
very  much our  science  given the  proposed  S/N of  15. The  largest
structures should  not have  scales larger than  5-10 arcsec  based on
Herschel  images  so that  no  ACA is  needed.   We  use the  physical
properties of GMCs  observed in the Local Group  dwarfs (Rosolowsky \&amp;
Leroy  2006, Hughes et  al. 2013)  to set  up the  spatial resolution,
velocity resolution and exposure time.   A beam size of 1.5 arcsec (10
pc) is used given that GMCs in dwarfs have a minimum size of 10 pc.  A
1  km/s velocity  resolution is  employed given  the  typical velocity
dispersion  of  ~  5  km/s  for  GMCs in  dwarfs.   The  peak  CO
brightness temperature of  the Local Group GMCs are  around 1-4 K.  To
probe  the median  value of  2.5 K  at 15  sigma, the  requested on
source exposure is 40 mins for one pointing with the total duration of
2.5 hrs.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
